<paragraph blockId="5.[595,732,856,880]" box="[595,732,856,880]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
(
<figureCitation box="[602,724,856,880]" captionStart-0="Figs 18–23" captionStart-1="Figs 24–27" captionStartId-0="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionStartId-1="7.[133,170,879,898]" captionTargetBox-0="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetBox-1="[137,1126,220,856]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="7" captionText-0="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." captionText-1="Figs 24–27. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 24 – front tarsus; 25 – hind femur and tibia; 26 – wing; 27 – subcosta." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252155" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6252155/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Figs 18–27</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[133,1155,903,1724]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
Dia gno sis (male). In the key to the males of the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="DISNEY R. H. L." box="[900,1040,903,927]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7257" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8): 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 161, but as the epandrial hairs are somewhat robust along the lower margins one could take either option. At couplet 162 lead 1 is for 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[673,925,964,988]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinicincta">
<emphasis box="[673,830,965,988]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">M. spinicincta</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
, whose hypopygium resembles the new species but with a shorter dorsal face to the epandrium (
<figureCitation box="[981,1109,995,1019]" captionStart="Figs 28–30" captionStartId="7.[133,170,1692,1711]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,964,1663]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 28–30. Megaselia spinicincta (Wood) male: 28–30 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6290587" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6290587/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Figs 28–30</figureCitation>
). In addition it has only two bristles on the notopleuron, a costal index less than 0.5 (
<figureCitation box="[1003,1081,1025,1050]" captionStart="Figs 31–32" captionStartId="8.[133,170,622,641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1149,220,593]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 31–32. Megaselia spinicincta (Wood) male: 31 – front tarsus; 32 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252159/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) and a posterodorsal hair palisade on segment 1–4 of the front tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[856,941,1056,1080]" captionStart="Figs 31–32" captionStartId="8.[133,170,622,641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1149,220,593]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 31–32. Megaselia spinicincta (Wood) male: 31 – front tarsus; 32 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252159/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). Taking lead 2 at couplet 162 one proceeds to couplet 187, where the choice is between the vein Sc running to vein 1 or falling just short of it. As the Sc is only just short of vein 1 (
<figureCitation box="[973,1058,1118,1142]" captionStart="Figs 24–27" captionStartId="7.[133,170,879,898]" captionTargetBox="[137,1126,220,856]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 24–27. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 24 – front tarsus; 25 – hind femur and tibia; 26 – wing; 27 – subcosta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252155/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
), at low magnifications it may appear to join vein 1. Taking the first option one proceeds to couplet 194, to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmitz)" baseAuthorityName="Schmitz" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[220,453,1179,1203]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubella">
<emphasis box="[220,336,1179,1203]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">M. rubella</emphasis>
(Schmitz)
</taxonomicName>
, whose epandrium has fewer and much finer hairs; as does the subsequently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1989" box="[390,569,1209,1233]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanoi">
<emphasis box="[390,487,1209,1233]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">M. kanoi</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
that runs to the same point. Taking the second option at couplet 187 one proceeds to couplet 204, where the separation is between a yellow haltere knob or one that is variably darker. The first option leads to couplet 232, lead 2, where one is returned to a complex that all have fewer and weaker epandrial hairs. Taking the second option from couplet 204 one arrives at couplet 388 and 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1988" box="[660,908,1332,1356]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="invernessae">
<emphasis box="[660,822,1333,1356]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">M. invernessae</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
, whose epandrial hairs are likewise weaker and fewer. Indeed the hypopygium of the new species is closer to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinicincta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">M. spinicincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to any other subsequently described species running to any of the above couplets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[133,1155,903,1724]" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">
Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[357,436,1455,1479]" captionStart="Figs 18–23" captionStartId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
and with dense but very fine microtrichia. Cheek with 5–7 fine bristles and jowl with a single very long bristle. Postpedicels as 
<figureCitation box="[874,955,1486,1510]" captionStart="Figs 18–23" captionStartId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
and without SPS vesicles. Palps yellow, about a third as broad as postpedicel, with 4 bristles and as many hairs. Labrum pale. Labella as 
<figureCitation box="[491,576,1547,1571]" captionStart="Figs 18–23" captionStartId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
. Thorax brown. Three notopleural bristles, but the middle one is the smallest (
<figureCitation box="[465,551,1578,1602]" captionStart="Figs 18–23" captionStartId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with numerous hairs that are longest posterolaterally on T6. Venter brown, and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[680,806,1670,1694]" captionStart="Figs 18–23" captionStartId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" captionTargetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 18–23. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="16">Figs 22–23</figureCitation>
. Legs yellow apart from brown tip to hind femur.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252149" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6252149" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252149/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" startId="6.[133,170,1364,1383]" targetBox="[137,1148,250,1335]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[133,1154,1364,1715]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">
Figs 18–23. 
<taxonomicName authority="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST, 2018" authorityName="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST" authorityYear="2018" box="[250,471,1364,1383]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horrenticauda" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[250,471,1364,1383]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Megaselia horrenticauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[482,533,1365,1384]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male: 18 – frons; 19 – postpedicels; 20 – labella and palps; 21 – notopleuron; 22–23 – hypopygium.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[133,1154,1364,1715]" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">
Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–3 only (
<figureCitation box="[916,1003,1414,1439]" captionStart="Figs 24–27" captionStartId="7.[133,170,879,898]" captionTargetBox="[137,1126,220,856]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 24–27. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 24 – front tarsus; 25 – hind femur and tibia; 26 – wing; 27 – subcosta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252155/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.6 times its length. Hind femur and tibia as 
<figureCitation box="[1009,1089,1445,1469]" captionStart="Figs 24–27" captionStartId="7.[133,170,879,898]" captionTargetBox="[137,1126,220,856]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 24–27. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 24 – front tarsus; 25 – hind femur and tibia; 26 – wing; 27 – subcosta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252155/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
. Hind tibia with up to 24 only moderately differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[640,793,1506,1531]" captionStart="Figs 24–27" captionStartId="7.[133,170,879,898]" captionTargetBox="[137,1126,220,856]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 24–27. Megaselia horrenticauda n. sp. male: 24 – front tarsus; 25 – hind femur and tibia; 26 – wing; 27 – subcosta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252155/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="17">Figs 26 &amp; 27</figureCitation>
) 2.0– 
<quantity box="[858,942,1507,1531]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.52. Costal ratios 2.0: 0.9: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[748,843,1537,1561]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
long. No hair at base of vein 3. With 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outer be 
<quantity box="[642,737,1568,1592]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Haltere knob pale gray.
</paragraph>
